INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('0365df0b-bc26-4abc-ae31-08df5d693e6c','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','cs-ticket-resolution','Investigates and resolves ZaloPay lending (Cashloan) customer-support JIRA tickets. Reads the ticket, classifies the issue, investigates loan/log/partner data, posts a root-cause comment in JIRA wiki markup, and decides whether to auto-close. Use when given a JIRA ticket ID (e.g. ISSUE-12345, LENDING-123, CSKH-456), when asked to check/investigate/resolve a CS ticket, or when a customer complains about a loan application (registration, OTP, contract signing, disbursement, repayment) with partner SHB, CAKE, or TNEX.','---\nname: cs-ticket-resolution\ndescription: Investigates and resolves ZaloPay lending (Cashloan) customer-support JIRA tickets. Reads the ticket, classifies the issue, investigates loan/log/partner data, posts a root-cause comment in JIRA wiki markup, and decides whether to auto-close. Use when given a JIRA ticket ID (e.g. ISSUE-12345, LENDING-123, CSKH-456), when asked to check/investigate/resolve a CS ticket, or when a customer complains about a loan application (registration, OTP, contract signing, disbursement, repayment) with partner SHB, CAKE, or TNEX.\n---\n\n\n# CS Ticket Resolution\n\nInvestigate and resolve Cashloan customer-support JIRA tickets.\n\nKnowledge base (policies, error-code meanings) lives in Confluence and is reached via `search_knowledge`. This skill does NOT embed error-code tables or policy text — look them up.\n\n## Core principles (these are where this task historically fails)\n\n1. **Never read an error code by its literal English label.** `-18 \"upload image fail\"` or `\"StepCode invalid\"` usually means something else (identity-doc mismatch, expired contract, ineligibility). Decode every code via `search_knowledge`. If a code is not in the KB, you do NOT know the cause — leave the ticket open.\n2. **Do not trust reporter-supplied facts.** The CS-reported timestamp, the channel (\"gửi Noti\"), \"không huỷ được\" are often wrong. Verify against the loan\'s actual state/log history; widen the search window when the reported window is empty.\n3. **A partner error (TNEX 400, `response=null`) is a symptom, not a root cause.** It is usually the proximate trigger of an internal data/handler gap. \"Partner returned an error\" ≠ \"the partner owns the fix and we have nothing to do.\"\n4. **Answer the question the customer actually asked.** Confirming loan state ≠ answering \"why was I rejected?\" or \"can I cancel and re-register?\".\n5. **Separate CS-actionable-now from needs-engineering.** Most real resolutions are a CS instruction (re-apply / pick the new ward / wait until due date), not an eng investigation. Always give the CS-facing line.\n\n## Execution modes\n\nDetect from the invocation prompt before Step 1.\n- **Interactive (default):** a human is present. Step 6 drafts the comment and waits for confirmation before `comment_jira`.\n- **Autonomous:** no user (prompt says \"scheduled job\" / \"auto-resolve\" / \"no user to confirm\"). Step 6 posts directly, but only if confidence is high; otherwise skip the comment and log why.\n\nStep 7 (auto-close) is identical in both modes — the agent decides on its own.\n\n## Workflow\n\nCopy this checklist and track progress:\n\n```\n- [ ] 1. Read, parse, dedup (capture the customer\'s explicit ask)\n- [ ] 2. Triage & classify\n- [ ] 3. KB-first lookup (+ decode every error code)\n- [ ] 4. Investigate (newest loan first)\n- [ ] 5. Analyze root cause (CS-actionable vs needs-eng)\n- [ ] 6. Post the comment\n- [ ] 7. Auto-close decision (read reference/autoclose-gates.md first)\n```\n\n### Step 1: Read, parse & dedup\n1. `read_jira_ticket` with the ticket ID.\n2. `get_jira_comments` for prior context.\n3. Extract: `zalopay_id`, `loan_application_id`, `event_time`, `partner_code`, and the customer\'s **explicit ask** (one sentence — you must answer it in Step 6).\n4. **Dedup:** if the same CS \"Ticket <number>\" or `loan_application_id` appears across multiple JIRA issues, treat them as ONE case (investigate once, cross-link). Real example: ISSUE-38443/38444 were the same customer analyzed twice with divergent conclusions.\n\n### Step 2: Triage & classify\nPick ONE class — it controls investigation depth, CTA shape, and auto-close eligibility.\n\n| Class | Signal | Auto-close path |\n|-------|--------|-----------------|\n| `self_recovered` | newest loan in terminal-success (FINISH/COMPLETED/code 0) AND success timestamp is AFTER ticket creation | eligible → `communication` |\n| `working_as_designed` | matches a known policy (settlement-sync timing, DPD payment window, contract end-date) | eligible → `communication` (needs KB cite) |\n| `partner_decision` | partner rejected / ineligible / credit decision | usually LEAVE OPEN unless KB gives a complete customer instruction |\n| `technical_error` | genuine system/integration defect, no benign explanation | LEAVE OPEN (internal fix pending) |\n| `user_misunderstanding` | wrong expectation; reporter facts don\'t match system | eligible only if you can fully explain self-serve |\n| `product_feedback` | \"Góp ý / feedback\", no loan, no error | route; do NOT auto-close as resolved |\n| `out_of_scope` | not Cashloan, or partner ∉ {SHB, CAKE, TNEX} | bounce politely; do NOT auto-close |\n| `duplicate` | same loan/customer as another ticket | follow the primary ticket |\n\nScope: Cashloan supports ONLY **SHB / CAKE / TNEX**. Prefixed titles like `[3036 - SHB Finance]`, `[4747 - TNEX]` map to in-scope partners. Out of scope → tell the reporter politely and request a ticket review; do not fabricate an investigation.\n\n### Step 3: KB-first lookup\n`search_knowledge` for the symptom + class AND for **every error code** you see (by code string). A clear KB match is your root cause + the basis for a terminal CTA. No usable match → that is an auto-close blocker, and a candidate to propose for the Confluence KB.\n\n### Step 4: Investigate\nAnalyze the **newest loan application first**. Tool selection, mandatory error-code decoding, the don\'t-trust-the-window rule, `response=null` handling, and the OpenSearch trace drill-down pattern are in **[reference/investigation.md](reference/investigation.md)** — read it before digging into logs.\n\n### Step 5: Analyze root cause\nWrite down: root cause (with the **decoded** code meaning, never the raw label); which step stalled; resolved vs ongoing; whether a **pending internal remediation** exists (dev fix, data backfill, manual CS workaround → not closeable); and split the conclusion into (a) what CS can tell the customer NOW and (b) optional eng/partner follow-up. Max 2 enrichment rounds; if still insufficient, note uncertainty + recommend escalation (that uncertainty is a correct auto-close blocker).\n\n### Step 6: Post the comment\n**Interactive:** present the summary, draft the comment, then ask:\n> Đây là nội dung comment mình đề xuất cho ticket [ID]. Bạn xác nhận để mình post lên JIRA nhé?\n\nOnly `comment_jira` after explicit approval.\n\n**Autonomous:** compose, re-check confidence — if root cause is unknown, KB missed, or you\'d use hedging (\"có thể\", \"chưa rõ\", \"cần kiểm tra\"), do NOT comment (log + exit). Otherwise `comment_jira`, then Step 7.\n\nUse JIRA wiki markup (NOT Markdown). The CTA MUST carry a customer/CS-facing terminal line; eng follow-up is a separate sub-line, never a substitute:\n\n```\nh3. *Nguyên nhân*: [decoded root cause — no raw literal code labels]\n\nh3. *CTA*:\n* *Cho KH/CS*: [terminal action CS can relay now]\n* *Cho team kỹ thuật* (nếu có): [eng/partner follow-up]\n\nh3. *Tham khảo* (KB / jira links)\n* [Title|URL]\n\n{quote}\n[DEBUG] investigation report\n\nh3. Thông tin ticket\n* *ZaloPay ID*: [value]\n* *Loan Application ID*: [value]\n* *Event time*: [value]\n* *Partner*: [value | verified via loan record]\n* *Câu hỏi của KH*: [the explicit ask from Step 1]\n\nh3. Phân loại ticket\n* *Class*: [self_recovered | working_as_designed | partner_decision | technical_error | user_misunderstanding | product_feedback | out_of_scope | duplicate]\n* *Recommended Action*: [CTA]\n\nh3. Kết quả tra cứu\n* Loan status / Current step / Code (+ decoded meaning)\n\nh3. Nguyên nhân\n[Root cause or \"unknown + escalation\"]\n\nh3. Log lỗi (nếu có)\n{code}[error logs]{code}\n\nh3. Giải pháp\n[Specific resolution or escalate]\n\nh3. Tham khảo\n* [Title|URL]\n{quote}\n```\n\n### Step 7: Auto-close decision\nAfter `comment_jira` succeeds, decide on your own whether to call `mark_done_cs_ticket` — do NOT ask the user. **Default to LEAVE OPEN.** Auto-close requires passing every gate.\n\n**Before deciding, read [reference/autoclose-gates.md](reference/autoclose-gates.md)** — re-read your own comment against the Gate A blockers and Gate B positives there. A recent PROD audit found 3 of 6 actual auto-closes were wrong; the gates exist precisely to catch that. For worked real-ticket examples, see [reference/casebook.md](reference/casebook.md).\n\n## Rules\n\n- **JIRA wiki syntax:** `h3.` headers, `*bold*`, `*` bullets, `{code}` blocks, `[text|url]` links.\n- **Partner-specific:** use ONLY data matching the exact `partner_code`, verified via the loan record.\n- **Auto-post gated by mode:** Interactive → confirm before `comment_jira`; Autonomous → post only if confidence is high.\n- **Self-evaluate before closing:** your own CTA language is the signal. A false-close (hidden customer issue) costs far more than a false-open (manual review later).\n- **Partner support:** ONLY SHB, CAKE, TNEX. Otherwise inform the reporter and request a ticket review.\n- **Propose KB gaps:** when KB lookup misses on a recurring pattern or error code, note it so it can be added to Confluence (so future `search_knowledge` finds it).\n\n## Reference files\n\n- **[reference/investigation.md](reference/investigation.md)** — tool selection, mandatory error-code decoding, don\'t-trust-the-window, `response=null`, trace drill-down.\n- **[reference/autoclose-gates.md](reference/autoclose-gates.md)** — Gate A blockers, Gate B positives, the decision + `root_cause_type`.\n- **[reference/casebook.md](reference/casebook.md)** — real-ticket calibration examples (JUSTIFIED vs RISKY vs PREMATURE).\n',NULL,'2026-06-08 06:04:42','2026-06-16 21:44:03');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('3948e922-8caf-4c25-aada-3d6e2b490851','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','investigate-partner-issue','Fetch partner-side HTTP request/response logs from OpenSearch (services starting with `connector`, e.g. connector-shb / connector-cake / connector-tnex) and format them as a copy-ready block so QC can forward to the partner team for debugging during software testing. Activate when QC asks for \"partner log\", \"log connector\", \"log gửi đối tác\", \"request/response của đối tác\", \"log để partner debug\", or similar — and provides at least one of: trace.id, loan_application_id, or zalopay_id (event_time optional). Output pairs the outbound HTTP request with the inbound partner response per trace, masks internal secrets, and keeps business fields intact. Do NOT use for CS ticket root-cause analysis (that is `resolve_ticket`) — this skill only pulls and formats the partner log; it never comments on JIRA, closes tickets, or infers root cause.','---\nname: investigate-partner-issue\ndescription: \"Fetch partner-side HTTP request/response logs from OpenSearch (services starting with `connector`, e.g. connector-shb / connector-cake / connector-tnex) and format them as a copy-ready block so QC can forward to the partner team for debugging during software testing. Activate when QC asks for \\\"partner log\\\", \\\"log connector\\\", \\\"log gửi đối tác\\\", \\\"request/response của đối tác\\\", \\\"log để partner debug\\\", or similar — and provides at least one of: trace.id, loan_application_id, or zalopay_id (event_time optional). Output pairs the outbound HTTP request with the inbound partner response per trace, masks internal secrets, and keeps business fields intact. Do NOT use for CS ticket root-cause analysis (that is `resolve_ticket`) — this skill only pulls and formats the partner log; it never comments on JIRA, closes tickets, or infers root cause.\"\n---\n\n# Send Partner Log to QC\n\nFetch partner-side error logs (request + response) from OpenSearch and format them so QC can forward to the partner for debugging.\n\n## When to Activate\n\n- QC asks for \"partner log\", \"connector log\", \"request/response log to send to partner\"\n- During testing, QC hits a suspected partner-side error and needs evidence to report\n- The user provides a `trace.id`, `loan_application_id`, or `zalopay_id` and asks for the partner log\n- The user mentions a partner name (SHB / CAKE / TNEX) together with words like \"log\", \"debug\", \"request\", \"response\"\n\nIf the user is asking for the root cause of a CS ticket (not pulling logs for QC), use `resolve_ticket` instead.\n\n## Inputs Required\n\nQC MUST provide AT LEAST ONE of the following three identifiers:\n\n- `trace.id` (preferred — shortest path)\n- `loan_application_id`\n- `zalopay_id` (user_id)\n\nIf QC provides multiple, prefer in this order: `trace.id` > `loan_application_id` > `zalopay_id`.\n\n`get_logs_by_trace_id` is ALWAYS the final fetch step — only it returns the complete cross-service trace we then filter for connector HTTP entries. Every other tool exists to surface a `trace_id` or bridge between identifiers. See Step 2 for the toolkit and reasoning patterns.\n\n`event_time` is **optional** but recommended to narrow the search window. If QC does not give it, use the tool\'s default `hours_delta` from `now`. If the result is empty, widen `hours_delta` and ask QC for an approximate time.\n\nIf QC does NOT provide any of the three identifiers → STOP and ask:\n> Để mình lấy được log connector của đối tác, bạn cho mình 1 trong 3: `trace.id`, `loan_application_id`, hoặc `zalopay_id`. Có thêm `event_time` (giờ xảy ra lỗi) thì càng tốt.\n\nOptional filters:\n- `partner_code` (SHB / CAKE / TNEX) — if present, prefer entries whose message contains the partner_code\n- `api_name` / `endpoint` — if QC names a specific API that failed\n\n## Workflow\n\nFollow these steps in order. Do NOT skip steps.\n\n### Step 1: Parse & Confirm Inputs\n\n1. Extract from QC\'s message: `trace.id` / `loan_application_id` / `zalopay_id` (need AT LEAST ONE), `event_time`, `partner_code`, `api_name`.\n2. Convert any relative time (\"yesterday\", \"10 AM\") to ISO before calling tools.\n3. If none of the three primary identifiers are present → STOP and ask QC using the template above. Do not guess, do not call tools with empty input.\n\n### Step 2: Resolve to a `trace_id`\n\nGoal: obtain **one or more `trace_id`s**. Do NOT filter for connector yet — that happens in Step 4 after the full trace is in hand.\n\nIf QC already provided `trace.id` → skip Step 2 and go straight to Step 3.\n\nOtherwise, you are an investigator. You have the toolkit below — choose, combine, and chain tools to surface a useful `trace_id`. The patterns below are starting points, not a fixed flowchart; if one path returns nothing, switch tool or chain through another identifier instead of giving up.\n\n**Toolkit cheatsheet**\n\n| Tool | Input | What it gives you |\n|------|-------|-------------------|\n| `get_activity_log` | `loan_application_id` (+ `event_time`) | Workflow / activity-component logs for that loan. Best when the loan ran a workflow (submission to partner, contract signing). Returns entries with `trace_id`. |\n| `search_http_errors` | `user_id` (zalopay_id) (+ `event_time`) | HTTP error logs for the user across services. Good for catching the failing call when you have the user identity. Returns entries with `trace_id`. |\n| `get_loan_detail` | `loan_application_id` | Loan record including the owner\'s `zalopay_id`, status, partner_code, timestamps. Use this to bridge `loan_application_id` → `zalopay_id` when needed. |\n| `get_customer_loans` | `zalopay_id` | All loans of the user. Use to bridge `zalopay_id` → a specific `loan_application_id` (e.g. newest). |\n| `get_logs_by_trace_id` | `trace_id` (+ `event_time`) | The full cross-service trace. Always the final fetch step. |\n\n**Common reasoning patterns** (illustrative — combine freely)\n\n- **Have `loan_application_id`, loan ran a workflow / partner submission failed**:\n  `get_activity_log` to pick a `trace_id` directly.\n- **Have `loan_application_id`, activity log is empty or doesn\'t show the partner call** (e.g. failure happened outside the workflow, or before activity was logged):\n  `get_loan_detail` to extract `zalopay_id` → `search_http_errors` to find the failing HTTP trace.\n- **Have `loan_application_id` and want richer signal**: do both — `get_activity_log` AND (`get_loan_detail` → `search_http_errors`). Compare to pick the most relevant `trace_id`.\n- **Have `zalopay_id`**: `search_http_errors` is the natural first pick. If the user has many loans and the symptom is loan-specific, you can also `get_customer_loans` → pick the newest → `get_activity_log` on that `loan_application_id`.\n- **Tool returns empty**: don\'t loop on the same tool — widen `hours_delta` ONCE, then switch tool / identifier chain.\n\nPick 1–3 `trace_id`s — newest first, or the ones closest to the reported symptom. Any service in the entry is fine here; the connector filter happens in Step 4.\n\nIf after exhausting reasonable tool combinations nothing comes back → tell QC: no logs in this window, suggest widening / adjusting `event_time` or providing a different identifier. Do NOT keep retrying the same tool with the same args.\n\n### Step 3: Pull the Full Trace\n\nFor each selected `trace_id` (max 3, prefer 1 if it\'s already clear):\n\n1. Call `get_logs_by_trace_id` with `trace_id` (+ `event_time` from the entry found in Step 2; or `now` if QC came in with the trace_id directly).\n2. This returns the complete cross-service trace. Keep the full result in hand — the connector filter happens next in Step 4.\n\n### Step 4: Filter to Connector HTTP & Pair Req/Resp\n\nFrom the full trace pulled in Step 3:\n\n1. Keep ONLY entries that satisfy BOTH:\n   - `service_name` starts with `connector` (e.g. `connector`, `connector-shb`, `connector-cake`, `connector-tnex`), AND\n   - the entry is an HTTP log (e.g. `component http`, or fields like `http.method`, `http.status_code`, `url`, `request_body`, `response_body`).\n2. DROP gRPC entries from connector services. gRPC traces are just internal wrappers of the same service — they do NOT contain the actual outbound HTTP call to the partner and are not useful for partner debugging.\n3. Within the remaining HTTP entries, identify the request / response PAIR:\n   - **Request**: outbound entry (we call partner). Usually carries `direction: outbound`, or `msg` contains \"request to partner\", the partner endpoint URL, the JSON body sent.\n   - **Response**: inbound entry (partner replies). Usually carries `direction: inbound`, an HTTP status code, the partner\'s JSON body, `error` if it failed.\n   - Pair them by matching `span_id` at the same level, or by closest timestamp if span data is missing.\n\nIf, after filtering, there is NO connector HTTP entry in the trace → tell QC the trace does not include a partner call (likely the failure happened upstream of the connector). Do NOT fall back to returning gRPC / internal-service logs.\n\nIf a request is present without its response → state explicitly \"partner did not respond / timeout\" and attach the request.\nIf a response is present without a clear request → still return the response, note that the request could not be captured.\n\n### Step 5: Sanity Check Before Output\n\nBefore handing the result to QC, self-check:\n\n- [ ] Every entry in the output belongs to `service_name` starting with `connector` AND is an HTTP log — NO other service, NO gRPC wrappers mixed in.\n- [ ] At least one partner request OR one partner response is present.\n- [ ] Timestamp, trace_id, endpoint/method, status, body are filled in as far as possible.\n- [ ] No internal secrets in the output to QC. If `Authorization`, `X-Api-Key`, `signature` headers contain real values → mask as `***`. Business fields (ID number, phone, amount) stay AS-IS — the partner needs them for reconciliation.\n\nIf check 1 or 2 fails → go back to Step 2/3, widen `hours_delta` or switch trace.\n\n### Step 6: Format Output for QC\n\nOutput plain Markdown DIRECTLY in the reply — one section per `trace_id`. \n\nCRITICAL formatting rules:\n- DO NOT wrap the whole output in an outer ```` ``` ```` / ```` ```markdown ```` fenced block. The outer wrapper breaks rendering because the inner ```` ```json ```` fences collide with it (markdown does not support nested fences).\n- USE ```` ```json ```` fences ONLY around the actual JSON request/response bodies. Everything else (headers, status, notes, partner info) is plain Markdown (`##`, `###`, `- **key**: value`).\n- One trace = one `## Partner log — trace ...` section, followed by request / response / notes subsections. If you have multiple traces, repeat the whole section, no outer wrapper.\n\nTemplate (this is what you EMIT verbatim — no leading/trailing ```` ``` ````):\n\n## Partner log — trace `{trace_id}`\n\n- **Partner**: {partner_code or inferred from service_name}\n- **Service**: {service_name, e.g. connector-shb}\n- **Time**: {timestamp of the first request}\n- **Endpoint**: {method} {url/path}\n- **Status**: {http status / partner error code}\n\n### Request\n\n```json\n{request body / params, pretty-printed if JSON}\n```\n\nHeaders (only relevant ones, secrets masked):\n- `Content-Type: ...`\n- `X-Partner-Code: ...`\n\n### Response\n\n```json\n{response body, pretty-printed}\n```\n\n- HTTP status: {code}\n- Error (if any): {error message / partner error code}\n\n### Notes (optional)\n- {Single-line observation, e.g. \"Partner returned 500 with empty body\"; \"Timeout after 30s\"; \"Response code 09 = invalid OTP per partner spec\"}\n\nAfter the output, add ONE summary line for QC, e.g.:\n\n> Đã lấy được log connector cho `{identifier}`. Bạn forward block trên cho đội đối tác `{partner}` để họ debug. Nếu cần thêm trace khác báo mình.\n\n### Step 7: Don\'t Auto-Action\n\nThis skill ONLY pulls logs for QC to forward themselves. Do NOT:\n- Comment on JIRA.\n- Close a ticket.\n- Call the partner.\n- Infer a root cause like `resolve_ticket` does — that\'s QC\'s / integration team\'s job once they have the log.\n\n## Rules\n\n- **`get_logs_by_trace_id` is the final fetch**: regardless of which identifier QC supplied, the connector req/resp comes from `get_logs_by_trace_id`. The other tools only exist to surface a `trace_id`.\n- **Connector filter is MANDATORY and POST-fetch**: filter for `service_name` starting with `connector` AND HTTP component AFTER the full trace is pulled, not before. Internal services (cashloan-core, lending-bff, …) must never leak into output destined for the partner.\n- **HTTP only, drop gRPC**: connector partner calls are HTTP. gRPC entries on connector services are internal-service wrappers, not the real partner call — exclude them.\n- **Pair req/resp**: always try to pair request with response. A lone response without a request is almost useless to the partner.\n- **Mask internal secrets**: tokens / api keys / signatures in headers must be replaced with `***` before showing to QC. Business data stays unchanged.\n- **Do not fabricate**: if the trace has no partner response, say so explicitly — do not synthesize.\n- **Scope cap**: at most 3 traces per call. If QC needs more, they re-invoke with a specific `trace_id`.\n- **Partner support**: prioritise SHB / CAKE / TNEX. Other partners still get logs if found, but flag \"partner outside the standard scope\".\n- **No silent empty**: if nothing is found, return a clear message + suggested next step (widen `event_time` or switch identifier). Never return an empty output silently.\n','{}','2026-05-28 03:25:15','2026-06-16 21:43:56');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('3dafd1ef-bc7a-4b9e-bd0d-ddd172075140','f1eab81b-eedc-455d-8b19-dccdd3d0754e','openapi-validation','Validates OpenAPI specifications against custom API guidelines including path casing, standard error schemas, and security headers.','---\nname: openapi-validation\ndescription: Validates OpenAPI specifications against custom API guidelines including path casing, standard error schemas, and security headers.\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# OpenAPI Spec Validation Skill\n\nThis skill ensures that OpenAPI specifications adhere to internal API design guidelines. You will analyze the provided OpenAPI spec (JSON or YAML) and validate it against the custom rules.\n\n## Process\n\n1. **Load Rules:** Read the `rules/openapi_rules.json` file to understand the specific validation rules.\n2. **Analyze Spec:** Inspect the provided OpenAPI document.\n3. **Validate:** Check for the following categories:\n   - **Path Casing:** Ensure all paths match the specified casing rule (e.g., lowercase kebab-case).\n   - **Error Schemas:** Verify that all `4xx` and `5xx` responses reference the standard error schema.\n   - **Security Headers:** Ensure required security headers (e.g., Authorization or API keys) are defined globally or on specific endpoints where required.\n   - **Metadata:** Check for required `info` fields (title, version, description).\n4. **Report:** Generate a validation report listing:\n   - ✅ Passed checks\n   - ❌ Violations (with exact path/location in the spec and the reason)\n   - ⚠️ Warnings for best practices\n\n## Action\nWhen a user asks to review or validate an OpenAPI spec, load the rules and apply the validation process above, returning a clear and structured report.\n',NULL,'2026-06-09 10:46:12','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('3dfd791a-9cdb-433f-be5d-df06d14d1c42','cf004684-86a3-48d1-b09e-32a6c6e7de3a','metabase-assistant','Assists with writing Metabase SQL queries, configuring field filters, creating custom expressions, and designing dashboards.','---\nname: metabase-assistant\ndescription: Assists with writing Metabase SQL queries, configuring field filters, creating custom expressions, and designing dashboards.\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# Metabase Assistant\n\nYou are an expert data analyst and Metabase administrator. Your goal is to help users write optimized SQL queries, configure Metabase-specific features (like variables and Field Filters), write custom expressions, and design effective dashboards.\n\n## Core Responsibilities\n\n1. **SQL Query Generation & Optimization:**\n   - Write SQL queries tailored to the user\'s database dialect (PostgreSQL, MySQL, Snowflake, etc.).\n   - Incorporate Metabase variables using the correct syntax.\n   - Ensure queries are optimized for performance, especially when powering dashboard cards.\n\n2. **Metabase Variables & Field Filters:**\n   - Use standard variables `{{variable_name}}` for simple text/number inputs.\n   - Use optional clauses `[[ WHERE column = {{variable_name}} ]]` to handle cases where a filter might be empty.\n   - Correctly implement **Field Filters** (which map directly to a column) without using column names or operators in the SQL. Example: `[[ WHERE {{created_at_filter}} ]]`.\n\n3. **Custom Expressions:**\n   - Assist users in writing custom aggregations and metrics using Metabase\'s custom expression builder (e.g., `SumIf`, `CountIf`, `regexextract`).\n\n4. **Dashboard & Visualization Best Practices:**\n   - Recommend the best visualization type for the requested data (e.g., line chart for time series, bar chart for categorical comparison, number for KPIs).\n   - Suggest dashboard layouts that highlight key metrics first.\n\n## Process\n\n- When asked to write a query, clarify the SQL dialect if not provided.\n- Always check if the user needs filters on the dashboard. If so, provide the SQL with Metabase optional variable syntax.\n- Consult the `docs/metabase_cheat_sheet.md` for exact syntax rules when generating responses.\n- Explain *how* to map the variables in the Metabase UI (e.g., \"Set this variable type to \'Field Filter\' and map it to the `orders.created_at` column\").\n',NULL,'2026-06-09 22:33:51','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('c157d419-2688-4216-ad4d-39721373ec68','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','sql-query-builder','Generate Redshift SQL queries for ZaloPay Metabase covering BNPL/Paylater, Cash Loan, and Payment data. Use this skill whenever the user wants to query, analyze, pull data, build a dashboard query, write SQL, run a cohort/funnel/retention analysis, or asks \"how many users / how much volume / what\'s the conversion\" for any ZaloPay lending or payment domain — even if Metabase isn\'t explicitly mentioned. Trigger on phrases like \"write a query\", \"pull data on\", \"SQL for\", \"cohort\", \"funnel\", \"MoM\", \"DoD\", \"conversion rate\", \"disbursement volume\", \"BNPL users\", \"cash loan partners\", \"IBFT\", \"TF024/TF029\", or any reference to known table/partner names (CIMB, CAKE, TNEX, SHB, LFVN, VietCredit, VPB).','---\nname: sql-query-builder\ndescription: \"Generate Redshift SQL queries for ZaloPay Metabase covering BNPL/Paylater, Cash Loan, and Payment data. Use this skill whenever the user wants to query, analyze, pull data, build a dashboard query, write SQL, run a cohort/funnel/retention analysis, or asks \\\"how many users / how much volume / what\'s the conversion\\\" for any ZaloPay lending or payment domain — even if Metabase isn\'t explicitly mentioned. Trigger on phrases like \\\"write a query\\\", \\\"pull data on\\\", \\\"SQL for\\\", \\\"cohort\\\", \\\"funnel\\\", \\\"MoM\\\", \\\"DoD\\\", \\\"conversion rate\\\", \\\"disbursement volume\\\", \\\"BNPL users\\\", \\\"cash loan partners\\\", \\\"IBFT\\\", \\\"TF024/TF029\\\", or any reference to known table/partner names (CIMB, CAKE, TNEX, SHB, LFVN, VietCredit, VPB).\"\n---\n\n# Metabase Query (ZaloPay)\nGenerate Redshift SQL for Zalopay\'s datawarehouse\n\n## Workflow\n\n1. **Identify the domain** — BNPL/Paylater, Cash Loan, Payment, or cross-domain. Domain determines which schema reference to load.\n2. **Load the relevant schema reference(s)** from `references/` before writing SQL. Never write a query against a table without first reading its schema file.\n3. **Load `references/query-patterns.md`** if the question is a cohort / funnel / retention / blended-rate / MoM analysis — these have standard shapes.\n4. **Write the query** following the SQL conventions below.\n5. **Return the SQL support to another skill or request from user. Only visualize SQL if user request.\n\nIf the schema reference does not contain a table or column needed for the question, STOP and tell the user — do not invent column names. Ask whether they want to add it to the schema doc, or whether you misunderstood which table they meant.\n\n## Schema references\n\nLoad only what\'s relevant to the question. Each file is self-contained.\n\n- `references/schema-bnpl.md` — Paylater tables: fees (`paylater_fee_mart`), transaction log (`paylater_account_log_mart`), account snapshots (`paylater_account_mart_real` — credit limits, balances, DPD, status). Partners: CIMB, CAKE, TNEX, SHB.\n- `references/schema-cashloan.md` — Cash Loan book: `datawarehouse.cashloan_active_loans_mart` (active + settled loans — principal, outstanding, overdue, term, loan economics in the `loan_info` SUPER column, partner-specific workflow/balance data in the `partner_data` SUPER column). Partner values seen in data: CAKE, SHB, TNEX (others e.g. LFVN, VietCredit, VPB may appear).\n- `references/schema-payment.md` — Payment tables incl. IBFT (TF024, TF029), appID 241.\n- `references/schema-shared.md` — Cross-domain dimensions: users, partners, dates, status enums.\n- `references/query-patterns.md` — Reusable analytical patterns (cohort retention, funnel, blended rate, MoM/DoD trends).\n\nIf the question spans multiple domains (e.g., \"BNPL users who also took a Cash Loan\"), load both schema files plus `schema-shared.md`.\n\n## SQL conventions (non-negotiable)\n\nThese are house rules. Apply them every time unless the user explicitly overrides.\n\n### Dialect\n- **Redshift (AWS).** Use Redshift-specific syntax: `DATEADD`, `DATEDIFF`, `DATE_TRUNC`, `LISTAGG`, `||` for concat, `EXTRACT(...)`. Avoid Postgres-only or Presto-only functions.\n\n### Time zone\n- All timestamp fields are stored in UTC. **Always** convert to local time using `<timestamp_column> AT TIME ZONE \'asia/ho_chi_minh\'` before any date truncation, filtering by date, or display.\n- Pattern: `DATE_TRUNC(\'day\', created_at AT TIME ZONE \'asia/ho_chi_minh\') AS day_vn`\n\n### Date filter (mandatory)\n- **Always include a date filter limiting to the last 3 months** unless the user specifies a different window. This protects against runaway queries on large tables.\n- Standard pattern:\n  ```sql\n  WHERE created_at AT TIME ZONE \'asia/ho_chi_minh\'\n        >= DATEADD(month, -3, DATE_TRUNC(\'month\', CURRENT_TIMESTAMP AT TIME ZONE \'asia/ho_chi_minh\'))\n  ```\n- If the user gives an explicit window (e.g., \"Feb 2026\", \"last 7 days\", \"Q1 2026\"), use that instead.\n\n### User counting\n- **Prefer `COUNT(DISTINCT user_id)` over `COUNT(*)`** for any user-level metric (active users, converters, retained users, etc.).\n- Use `COUNT(*)` only when the metric is truly row-based (e.g., transaction count, attempt count).\n\n### Structure\n- **Prefer CTEs (`WITH ... AS`) over subqueries.** One CTE per logical step. Name them clearly (`active_users`, `first_txn`, `monthly_cohort`).\n- Alias every table (short, readable: `u` for users, `t` for transactions, `p` for partners). Always qualify columns with the alias in JOINs.\n- Use `LEFT JOIN` deliberately — if you mean `INNER JOIN`, write `INNER JOIN`. Mixing them silently is a common bug.\n\n### Common pitfalls (Hai has flagged these before)\n- **Missing ELSE clause** in CASE statements → always include `ELSE NULL` or `ELSE \'unknown\'` explicitly.\n- **Redundant joins** → if a column is already in a CTE, don\'t re-join the source table.\n- **Unnecessary aggregations** → don\'t wrap a value in `MIN()` / `MAX()` if the GROUP BY guarantees one row per group already.\n- **Forgetting the timezone conversion** → daily aggregates will be off by 7 hours if you skip it.\n\n### Append-only tables — always dedupe by `update_time`\n\nMost ZaloPay `datawarehouse` tables are **append-only**: when a record changes, a new row is inserted with the same business ID (e.g., `fee_id`, `txn_id`, `loan_id`) and a later `update_time`. The same business ID can appear many times.\n\n**Rule:** Before any `SUM`, `COUNT(DISTINCT <business_id>)`, or record-level aggregation, dedupe to the latest version per business ID using `update_time` — **not** `sys_effective_date`.\n\n> **Column-name caveat:** the source update timestamp is called `update_time` on most tables, but some tables name it differently — e.g. `datawarehouse.cashloan_active_loans_mart` uses **`update_at`**. Always order by whatever the relevant schema file names as the source update timestamp; never by `sys_effective_date`.\n\n```sql\nWITH latest AS (\n    SELECT *\n    FROM (\n        SELECT\n            *,\n            ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY <business_id> ORDER BY update_time DESC) AS rn\n        FROM <table>\n        WHERE <date_filter>\n    )\n    WHERE rn = 1\n)\nSELECT ... FROM latest;\n```\n\nWhy `update_time` and not `sys_effective_date`: `sys_effective_date` is a warehouse-side timestamp that does not reliably reflect the true update order from the source system. `update_time` is the source-system update timestamp and is the authoritative ordering field.\n\n**Skip the dedupe only if:**\n- The user explicitly asks for change history / audit trail\n- The schema reference for that table explicitly says it\'s not append-only\n\nIf unsure whether a table is append-only, treat it as if it is (safer default — extra dedupe on a non-append-only table is a no-op).\n\n## Output format\n\nDefault response shape:\n\n> One short sentence describing what the query does.\n>\n> ```sql\n> -- Query here\n> ```\n>\n> *Assumptions/caveats (optional, 1-3 bullets):*\n> - Filter window: last 3 months (override if needed)\n> - Excludes test users (filter in CTE `clean_users`)\n\nDo not include a long explanation of every CTE unless the user asks. The SQL itself should be readable.\n\n## When the question is ambiguous\n\nIf the user\'s question could map to multiple tables or metrics (e.g., \"how many BNPL users?\" — registered? eligible? active? transacting?), pick the most likely interpretation, write the query, and call out the assumption in one line. Don\'t ask 3 questions before writing any SQL — write the most reasonable version and let the user redirect.\n\n### Always ask: which partner?\n\nThe one exception to \"write first, redirect later\" — if a query touches a column that identifies a partner (`partner_code` in `paylater_fee_mart`, `bank_code` in `paylater_account_log_mart`, or any equivalent in future tables) and the user has **not** specified which partner they want, **ask before generating SQL**. Do not default to \"all partners.\"\n\nWhy: ZaloPay\'s partner-level numbers are usually meaningless when blended (CIMB and LFVN have very different fee structures, populated fields, and volume profiles — see `schema-bnpl.md`). Returning a blended total is almost always wrong, and the user usually has a specific partner in mind.\n\nHow to ask:\n- Use the schema reference to list the known values for that table\'s partner column. Example: *\"Which partner — `CIMB`, `LFVN`, or both broken out separately?\"*\n- Always offer **\"both broken out separately\"** as an option (i.e., `GROUP BY partner_code`), since that\'s often what they actually want.\n- Do **not** offer \"all partners blended\" as an option — if they want that, they\'ll say so.\n\nOnce they answer, write the query.\n\n**Cross-table note:** `partner_code` (on `paylater_fee_mart`), `bank_code` (on `paylater_account_log_mart`), and `bank_code` (on `paylater_account_mart_real`) all refer to the same partner identity — the same value (e.g., `\'CIMB\'`) appears across all three. The join key between the three tables is `account_id` (fee_mart / log_mart) = `id` (account_mart_real).\n\n### Other ambiguity exceptions\n\nIf the user asks for something that requires a specific product code or status enum that isn\'t in the schema doc, ask which one they mean (or list the options from the schema file).\n',NULL,'2026-06-06 08:35:19','2026-06-16 22:36:27');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('dff4eb59-1303-11f1-b8d9-ceeb812e9e33','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','loan-investigation','Investigate loan application issues and errors','---\nname: loan-investigation\ndescription: Investigate loan application issues and errors\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# Loan Investigation\n\nWhen investigating a loan application issue:\n\n1. **Get loan details** using `get_loan_detail` with the loan_application_id\n2. **Check the status and code** fields:\n   - Status indicates the overall loan state\n   - Code and code_message give specific error/state info\n   - Current step shows where in the process the loan is\n3. **Review timeline**:\n   - created_at → submit_info_at → face_authen_at → approved_at → sign_contract_at\n   - Gaps or missing timestamps indicate where the process stalled\n4. **For error codes**, search the knowledge base using `search_knowledge` with the code/message\n5. **For HTTP errors**, use `search_http_errors` with the user_id around the event time\n6. **If trace IDs are found** in logs, use `get_logs_by_trace_id` to trace the full request flow\n\nCommon status codes:\n- Partner-specific codes vary by partner_code (check knowledge base)\n- Validation field may contain JSON with specific validation errors','{\"category\": \"domain\", \"priority\": 2}','2026-02-26 11:11:18','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('e00198f2-1303-11f1-b8d9-ceeb812e9e33','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','log-analysis','Analyze logs and trace errors','---\nname: log-analysis\ndescription: Analyze logs and trace errors\n---\n\n\n\n\n# Log Analysis\n\nWhen analyzing application logs:\n\n1. **Search by user ID** using `search_http_errors` to find error patterns:\n   - Set event_time to when the issue was reported\n   - Start with hours_delta=24, narrow down if too many results\n2. **Trace specific requests** using `get_logs_by_trace_id`:\n   - Look for trace IDs in the initial error search results\n   - Follow the request flow across services\n3. **Interpret log entries**:\n   - Level: error/warn/info indicates severity\n   - Trace ID: groups all logs for a single request\n   - Span ID: identifies specific service operations\n   - Error/Message: the actual error details\n4. **Common error patterns**:\n   - HTTP 4xx: client-side issues (bad request, auth failure)\n   - HTTP 5xx: server-side issues (internal error, timeout)\n   - gRPC errors: partner service connectivity issues\n   - Timeout errors: usually partner API slowness\n\n-- \nIf user request log to send partner(log of connector service, msg pattern \"[http Client] send request or [http Client] completed request\"), please send log with format\n- Path\n- Request(json)\n- Response(json)\n- HTTP code\n- Error(if have)','{\"category\": \"domain\", \"priority\": 3}','2026-02-26 11:11:18','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('e00db611-1303-11f1-b8d9-ceeb812e9e33','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','ticket-response','Write professional CS ticket responses','---\nname: ticket-response\ndescription: Write professional CS ticket responses\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# Ticket Response Guidelines\n\nWhen writing a comment on a CS ticket using `comment_jira`:\n\n## Format\n- Start with a brief summary of findings\n- List investigation steps taken\n- Provide root cause analysis\n- Recommend next steps or resolution\n- Use markdown formatting for readability\n\n## Tone\n- Professional and clear\n- Avoid technical jargon when possible\n- Be specific about findings (include IDs, timestamps, error codes)\n- If uncertain, clearly state what is known vs. unknown\n\n## Template\n```\n**Investigation Summary**\n\n**Issue:** [Brief description]\n\n**Investigation Steps:**\n1. [What was checked]\n2. [What was found]\n\n**Root Cause:** [Explanation]\n\n**Resolution/Next Steps:**\n- [Action items]\n\n**References:**\n- Loan ID: [if applicable]\n- Trace ID: [if applicable]\n- KB Article: [if applicable]\n```','{\"category\": \"workflow\", \"priority\": 1}','2026-02-26 11:11:19','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('e29a2cb8-d3ca-42c0-bf91-fbfa6cebb852','f1eab81b-eedc-455d-8b19-dccdd3d0754e','conventional-commits','Generates conventional commit messages based on code changes or descriptions.','---\nname: conventional-commits\ndescription: Generates conventional commit messages based on code changes or descriptions.\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# Conventional Commits Skill\n\nYou are an expert developer assistant specialized in writing clean, standard \"Conventional Commit\" messages. \n\n## Instructions\n1. When the user provides a code diff, a description of changes, or asks you to write a commit message, you must follow the strict guidelines outlined in the `rules/commit_rules.md` file.\n2. Analyze the provided changes to determine the most appropriate commit type (e.g., `feat`, `fix`, `chore`).\n3. Formulate a concise and clear subject line.\n4. If the changes are complex, provide an optional body explaining the *what* and *why* (not the *how*).\n5. Output the commit message inside a code block. Do not include extraneous chatter unless the user asks for an explanation of your choice.\n\n## Reference Files\n- Review the allowed prefixes and formatting guidelines in `rules/commit_rules.md` before generating the commit message.\n',NULL,'2026-06-09 11:17:47','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('ed0de62a-24d8-4562-8a7f-0c6c10e2900c','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','user-investigation','Analyze, investigate issue of user','---\nname: user-investigation\ndescription: Analyze, investigate issue of user\n---\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n# User Investigation\n\nWhen investigating a user issue:\n\n1. **Get loan details** using `get_customer_loans` with the user_id\n2. **For error codes**, search the knowledge base using `search_knowledge` with the code/message\n3. **For HTTP errors**, use `search_http_errors` with the user_id around the event time\n4. **If trace IDs are found** in logs, use `get_logs_by_trace_id` to trace the full request flow\n','{\"category\": \"workflow\", \"priority\": 3}','2026-02-27 04:37:22','2026-06-16 14:59:48');
INSERT INTO `skills` VALUES ('fbdd71f5-af17-4e67-b10d-b0a2b9601a32','00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001','visualize-data-structure','Prioritize data visualization whenever the response contains structured data, metrics, or trends capable of being visualized. Support: LineChart, AreaChart, BarChart, ComposedChart, PieChart, RingChart, FunnelChart, GaugeChart, HeatmapChart, HistogramChart, ScatterChart, WaterfallChart, SankeyChart.','---\nname: visualize-data-structure\ndescription: Prioritize data visualization whenever the response contains structured data, metrics, or trends capable of being visualized. Support: LineChart, AreaChart, BarChart, ComposedChart, PieChart, RingChart, FunnelChart, GaugeChart, HeatmapChart, HistogramChart, ScatterChart, WaterfallChart, SankeyChart.\n---\n\n# Chat JSON Render Output\n\n## Goal\n\nReturn compact visual chat answers as structured UI instead of raw markdown tables, JSX, React code, or SQL-seeded skill content.\n\nUse this skill when the answer benefits from structure: conclusions, CS investigation summaries, loan profile checks, user checks, loan trace results, trade/transaction flows, issue or ticket analysis, metrics, weekly/monthly comparisons, execution status, tool results, test results, file changes, and chart-like numeric reports.\n\nStrongly prefer `json-render` when the user says `check`, `kiểm tra`, `tra cứu`, `trade`, `transaction`, `giao dịch`, `hồ sơ vay`, or `user`, and the answer has structured facts or a step-by-step state flow such as OTP → disbursement → repayment sync, order/trade lifecycle, ticket investigation sequence, issue reproduction steps, retry timeline, or any trace that has success/failure checkpoints.\n\n## Output Contract\n\nPut one short natural-language sentence before the UI only when it helps. Then emit exactly one rendered UI block.\n\nChoose the output format:\n\n- Use `json-render` by default when the built-in components can express the result clearly: cards, metrics, charts, tables, steps, callouts, test results, file changes, and loan status cards. Format the output as JSON-render blocks using json-render chart primitives. Prefer `json-render/report` components for numeric summaries and KPI dashboards. Avoid raw text or standard markdown tables for complex data unless explicitly requested by the user.\n- Use `chat-html` only when the user explicitly asks for HTML or when a tool already produced an HTML fragment. The frontend normalizes `chat-html` through ReportRenderer, so keep it semantic and do not rely on CSS/classes for the visual outcome.\n- If the result explains what happened over time, render a visual timeline using `Steps` or `LoanStatusCard` instead of a plain bullet list.\n\nFor `json-render`, emit a fenced block labeled `json-render`.\n\nPrefer the official JSON Render flat shape for non-trivial UI:\n\n- `root`: id of the root element.\n- `elements`: object keyed by element id.\n- each element: `type`, `props`, and optional `children`.\n\nUse valid JSON only: double quotes, no comments, no trailing commas. Keep ids stable and readable, such as `summary-card`, `metrics-grid`, and `revenue-chart`.\n\nFor `chat-html`, emit a fenced block labeled `chat-html`.\n\nUse a self-contained semantic HTML fragment, not a full document. Prefer headings, paragraphs, lists, tables, blockquotes, and pre/code blocks. Do not depend on CSS, layout classes, or inline styles for the final visual appearance.\n\nPreferred loan/status card pattern:\n\n```json-render\n{\n  \"root\": \"loan-status\",\n  \"elements\": {\n    \"loan-status\": {\n      \"type\": \"LoanStatusCard\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Chi tiết Hồ sơ Vay\",\n        \"description\": \"Hồ sơ đã được TNEX duyệt và user đã ký hợp đồng. Đang chờ giải ngân.\",\n        \"statusLabel\": \"IN PROGRESS (Chờ giải ngân: QUERY_DISBURSEMENT)\",\n        \"statusTone\": \"warning\",\n        \"partner\": \"TNEX\",\n        \"amount\": \"15,000,000 VND\",\n        \"term\": \"9 tháng\",\n        \"loanId\": \"20260610-08022fa7-a266-4526-938e-ddb60e5aa15c\",\n        \"zalopayId\": \"260608000000032\",\n        \"contractId\": \"0101.02.0000022518\",\n        \"steps\": [\n          { \"title\": \"Tạo hồ sơ & Pass Rules\", \"detail\": \"Hoàn tất lúc 09:44:02\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"TNEX Phê duyệt\", \"detail\": \"Duyệt hạn mức 15,000,000 VND lúc 09:59:58\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Ký Hợp đồng\", \"detail\": \"Khách hàng xác nhận và ký hợp đồng thành công lúc 10:01:01\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Chờ Giải ngân\", \"detail\": \"Hệ thống đang truy vấn trạng thái giải ngân từ partner.\", \"status\": \"active\" }\n        ]\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nReplace all example values with retrieved evidence. Do not emit placeholder values in a real answer.\n\n## Examples\n\nUse these as compact shapes, not as facts. Replace every ID, amount, timestamp, count, status, and conclusion with retrieved evidence.\n\nUser or loan investigation with missing evidence:\n\n```json-render\n{\n  \"root\": \"report\",\n  \"elements\": {\n    \"report\": {\n      \"type\": \"Stack\",\n      \"props\": { \"direction\": \"vertical\", \"gap\": \"md\" },\n      \"children\": [\"summary\", \"metrics\", \"checks\", \"risk\"]\n    },\n    \"summary\": {\n      \"type\": \"Card\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Kết quả kiểm tra User 84901234567\",\n        \"description\": \"Chưa đủ bằng chứng để kết luận lỗi backend. Cần đối soát log OTP phía partner.\"\n      },\n      \"children\": [\"status\"]\n    },\n    \"status\": {\n      \"type\": \"Badge\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Cần điều tra thêm\", \"tone\": \"warning\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"metrics\": {\n      \"type\": \"Grid\",\n      \"props\": { \"columns\": \"3\" },\n      \"children\": [\"records\", \"errors\", \"owner\"]\n    },\n    \"records\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Loan records\", \"value\": \"0\", \"detail\": \"Không tìm thấy theo UserID\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"errors\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"HTTP errors\", \"value\": \"0\", \"detail\": \"Trong khung giờ kiểm tra\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"owner\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Owner kế tiếp\", \"value\": \"Partner\", \"detail\": \"Cần log OTP/client\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"checks\": {\n      \"type\": \"Steps\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"items\": [\n          { \"title\": \"Tra cứu hồ sơ vay\", \"detail\": \"Không tìm thấy record liên quan.\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Kiểm tra log backend\", \"detail\": \"Chưa thấy lỗi ZaloPay trong khoảng 10:00-10:30.\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Đối soát log OTP\", \"detail\": \"Chưa có log từ partner.\", \"status\": \"pending\" }\n        ]\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"risk\": {\n      \"type\": \"Callout\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Không chốt root cause khi thiếu log\",\n        \"content\": \"Thiếu bằng chứng OTP phía partner; chỉ có thể kết luận backend chưa ghi nhận hồ sơ trong khung giờ này.\",\n        \"tone\": \"warning\"\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nTransaction or trade trace with one failing checkpoint:\n\n```json-render\n{\n  \"root\": \"trace\",\n  \"elements\": {\n    \"trace\": {\n      \"type\": \"Stack\",\n      \"props\": { \"direction\": \"vertical\", \"gap\": \"md\" },\n      \"children\": [\"summary\", \"facts\", \"timeline\", \"blocker\"]\n    },\n    \"summary\": {\n      \"type\": \"Card\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Trace giao dịch TXN-20260617-0019\",\n        \"description\": \"Giao dịch đã tạo order thành công nhưng dừng ở bước partner callback.\"\n      },\n      \"children\": [\"badge\"]\n    },\n    \"badge\": {\n      \"type\": \"Badge\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Blocked: callback timeout\", \"tone\": \"error\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"facts\": {\n      \"type\": \"Grid\",\n      \"props\": { \"columns\": \"3\" },\n      \"children\": [\"amount\", \"partner\", \"window\"]\n    },\n    \"amount\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Amount\", \"value\": \"2,450,000 VND\", \"detail\": \"Payment amount\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"partner\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Partner\", \"value\": \"TNEX\", \"detail\": \"order_id ORD-8841\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"window\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Time window\", \"value\": \"14:02-14:07\", \"detail\": \"Asia/Ho_Chi_Minh\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"timeline\": {\n      \"type\": \"Steps\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"items\": [\n          { \"title\": \"Create order\", \"detail\": \"14:02:11 - API returned 200.\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Debit confirmed\", \"detail\": \"14:02:18 - Ledger entry posted.\", \"status\": \"done\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Partner callback\", \"detail\": \"14:07:18 - timeout after 300s.\", \"status\": \"error\" },\n          { \"title\": \"Retry reconciliation\", \"detail\": \"No retry job found yet.\", \"status\": \"pending\" }\n        ]\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"blocker\": {\n      \"type\": \"Callout\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Action needed\",\n        \"content\": \"Check partner callback logs for ORD-8841, then trigger reconciliation only if partner confirms final debit state.\",\n        \"tone\": \"error\"\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nKPI dashboard with chart data:\n\n```json-render\n{\n  \"root\": \"dashboard\",\n  \"elements\": {\n    \"dashboard\": {\n      \"type\": \"Stack\",\n      \"props\": { \"direction\": \"vertical\", \"gap\": \"md\" },\n      \"children\": [\"overview\", \"metrics\", \"chart\", \"note\"]\n    },\n    \"overview\": {\n      \"type\": \"Card\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Doanh số giải ngân theo tuần\",\n        \"description\": \"CAKE tăng 22.5% so với tuần trước, nhưng tỉ lệ lỗi callback cũng tăng.\"\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"metrics\": {\n      \"type\": \"Grid\",\n      \"props\": { \"columns\": \"3\" },\n      \"children\": [\"total\", \"growth\", \"callback-rate\"]\n    },\n    \"total\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Tổng giải ngân\", \"value\": \"42.5 tỷ VND\", \"detail\": \"Tuần 29/04\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"growth\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"WoW\", \"value\": \"+22.5%\", \"detail\": \"So với tuần 22/04\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"callback-rate\": {\n      \"type\": \"Metric\",\n      \"props\": { \"label\": \"Callback lỗi\", \"value\": \"1.8%\", \"detail\": \"+0.6 điểm %\" },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"chart\": {\n      \"type\": \"BarChart\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Giải ngân theo tuần\",\n        \"unit\": \"VND\",\n        \"data\": [\n          { \"label\": \"01/04\", \"value\": 28950000000 },\n          { \"label\": \"08/04\", \"value\": 31200000000 },\n          { \"label\": \"15/04\", \"value\": 34500000000 },\n          { \"label\": \"22/04\", \"value\": 38150000000 },\n          { \"label\": \"29/04\", \"value\": 42500000000 }\n        ]\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"note\": {\n      \"type\": \"Callout\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"title\": \"Điểm cần kiểm tra\",\n        \"content\": \"Tách callback lỗi theo partner trước khi kết luận lỗi vận hành hay lỗi tích hợp.\",\n        \"tone\": \"info\"\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nCommand or test result summary:\n\n```json-render\n{\n  \"root\": \"verification\",\n  \"elements\": {\n    \"verification\": {\n      \"type\": \"Stack\",\n      \"props\": { \"direction\": \"vertical\", \"gap\": \"md\" },\n      \"children\": [\"tests\", \"terminal\", \"files\"]\n    },\n    \"tests\": {\n      \"type\": \"TestResults\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"passed\": 5,\n        \"failed\": 1,\n        \"skipped\": 0,\n        \"failures\": [\n          { \"name\": \"reportSpec parses json-render fence\", \"message\": \"Expected root to equal report, received null.\" }\n        ]\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"terminal\": {\n      \"type\": \"Terminal\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"command\": \"node --test test/reportSpec.test.ts\",\n        \"output\": \"not ok 1 - reportSpec parses json-render fence\\n# Expected root to equal report, received null\",\n        \"exitCode\": 1\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    },\n    \"files\": {\n      \"type\": \"FileChange\",\n      \"props\": {\n        \"path\": \"ui/web/src/lib/report-spec.ts\",\n        \"kind\": \"modified\",\n        \"summary\": \"Parser now accepts json-render fences with leading prose.\",\n        \"additions\": 18,\n        \"deletions\": 4\n      },\n      \"children\": []\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSemantic HTML fallback only when the user asks for HTML or a tool already returned HTML:\n\n```chat-html\n<section>\n  <h2>Kết quả kiểm tra hồ sơ</h2>\n  <p>Hồ sơ đã được duyệt nhưng chưa có bằng chứng giải ngân thành công.</p>\n  <ul>\n    <li>Partner: TNEX</li>\n    <li>Contract: 0101.02.0000022518</li>\n    <li>Trạng thái cuối: QUERY_DISBURSEMENT</li>\n  </ul>\n  <blockquote>Cần đối soát callback giải ngân trước khi xác nhận tiền đã về ví.</blockquote>\n</section>\n```\n\n## Component Rules\n\nUse the active catalog first. Read `references/component-catalog.md` when you need exact props or want to check upstream JSON Render components.\n\nSupported now in cs-tool:\n\n- Layout/content: `Stack`, `Grid`, `Card`, `Heading`, `Text`, `Badge`, `Alert`, `Callout`, `Separator`, `Avatar`, `Icon`, `Image`, `Link`.\n- Static disclosure/overlay previews: `Accordion`, `Collapsible`, `Tabs`, `Carousel`, `Dialog`, `Drawer`, `DropdownMenu`, `Popover`, `Tooltip`, `Pagination`.\n- Static controls: `Button`, `ButtonGroup`, `Input`, `Textarea`, `Select`, `Checkbox`, `Radio`, `Switch`, `Slider`, `Toggle`, `ToggleGroup`.\n- Feedback/data/reporting: `Metric`, `Progress`, `Rating`, `Skeleton`, `Spinner`, `Table`, `Steps`, `LoanStatusCard`, `FileChange`, `CodeBlock`, `Terminal`, `TestResults`.\n- Charts: `AreaChart`, `BarChart`, `BarGraph`, `CandlestickChart`, `ChoroplethChart`, `ComposedChart`, `FunnelChart`, `Gauge`, `GaugeChart`, `HeatmapChart`, `HistogramChart`, `LineChart`, `LineGraph`, `LiveLineChart`, `PieChart`, `ProfitLossLine`, `RadarChart`, `RingChart`, `SankeyChart`, `ScatterChart`, `WaterfallChart`.\n- Chart helper preview: `Legend`.\n\nPrefer the mapped upstream JSON Render names when they make the report easier to scan. Unknown component names still render as fallback UI.\n\n## Style Rules\n\nUse the Refero Family style reference as the visual target: https://styles.refero.design/style/1bcae895-2245-4d33-aa43-1c1e80719554\n\n- Warm canvas/card surfaces: `#fbfaf9`, `#f8f7f4`, `#f2f0ed`.\n- Text should read graphite/charcoal, not pure black-heavy: `#343433`, `#474645`, muted `#848281`.\n- Use Ember Orange `#ff3e00` sparingly for links, progress, chart accent, and key highlights.\n- Prefer 10px cards, pill controls, flat inset borders, and concise labels.\n- Do not create decorative illustrations inside JSON Render specs; only use mapped components.\n- For `json-render`, keep the visual focused on data: one summary, metric tiles, a timeline/list, and one warning/error callout when relevant.\n- For semantic `chat-html`, use simple content tags that can be normalized into report components. Avoid fixed pixel widths that overflow mobile chat.\n- Use component statuses (`done`, `active`, `pending`, `error`) for timeline dots instead of drawing icons yourself.\n\n## Chart Rules\n\nWhen the user asks to query data, compare data, or check data, choose a chart intentionally instead of defaulting to a table.\n\n- `LineChart` / `AreaChart`: ordered trends over time, weekly/monthly movement, before/after trend.\n- `BarChart` / `BarGraph`: category comparison, partner comparison, top-N, side-by-side counts.\n- `ComposedChart`: volume plus rate, amount plus count, bar+line summaries.\n- `PieChart` / `RingChart`: share/mix when the parts sum to a meaningful whole.\n- `FunnelChart`: stage drop-off, onboarding or approval funnels.\n- `Gauge` / `GaugeChart`: one bounded KPI against a target or threshold.\n- `HeatmapChart`: density by time/status/segment, repeated checks over a grid.\n- `HistogramChart`: distribution buckets, ticket age ranges, latency bands, amount buckets.\n- `ScatterChart`: outliers, correlation, cluster checks.\n- `WaterfallChart`: delta, contribution, breakdown from base to final value.\n- `RadarChart`: multi-metric score comparison.\n- `ProfitLossLine`: positive/negative trend crossing zero.\n- `SankeyChart`: flow between states, sources, or ownership queues.\n\nPut simple chart points in `data` as objects with `label` and `value`.\n\nSpecialized charts can accept native-shaped data:\n\n- `CandlestickChart`: `data` rows with `label`/`date`, `open`, `high`, `low`, `close`.\n- `ChoroplethChart`: `data` as a GeoJSON `FeatureCollection`.\n- `HeatmapChart`: simple `{label,value}` points or heatmap columns with `bins`.\n- `HistogramChart`: bucket rows as `{label,value}` where `label` is the bucket/range.\n- `SankeyChart`: `nodes` array of `{name}` and `links` array of `{source,target,value}`.\n- `RadarChart`: simple `{label,value}` points, or `metrics` plus rows with `values`.\n- `WaterfallChart`: delta rows as `{label,value}` where positive values are gains and negative values are losses.\n\nFor VND or other large values, keep `value` numeric. The frontend compacts labels automatically, for example billions become `tỷ` and millions become `triệu`.\n\nIf data came from a Recharts-like answer, the renderer can normalize:\n\n- `xAxis.dataKey` as the label key.\n- first `series[].dataKey` as the numeric value key.\n- first `series[].name` as chart title.\n\n## Answer Patterns\n\nFor investigation reports, use:\n\n1. `Card` with a direct conclusion.\n2. `Grid` with `Metric` for headline facts.\n3. `Steps` for checked evidence and pending actions.\n4. `Callout` for uncertainty, blocker, or risk.\n\nFor bespoke loan trace cards, use `LoanStatusCard` when the data is a loan/profile state, otherwise use `Card` + `Grid` + `Metric` + `Steps` + `Callout`:\n\n1. Summary panel with final status badge.\n2. Three to four metric tiles for partner, amount, app code, contract, or duration.\n3. Timeline rows for successful and failed stages.\n4. Error callout with the exact failing function, partner response, timestamp, and actionability.\n\nFor issue, ticket, trace, trade, or transaction flows, use `json-render`:\n\n1. Summary panel with the final conclusion and severity/status badge.\n2. Key facts grid: ID, owner/partner, amount or scope, time window, current status.\n3. Step timeline in chronological order. Every step should show status (`done`, `active`, `pending`, or `error`), timestamp when known, and the evidence source.\n4. Root-cause or blocker callout with exact error text, failing function/API, response code, and what to do next.\n5. Keep unresolved or missing evidence visible as a warning row instead of omitting it.\n\nFor command or test summaries, use:\n\n1. `TestResults` for counts and failures.\n2. `Terminal` only for the relevant command output.\n3. `FileChange` only for concrete changed files.\n\nFor numeric reports, use:\n\n1. `Card` for title and subtitle.\n2. The chart type that matches the analytical intent, with real data only.\n3. `Metric` for totals, averages, latest value, or target delta when useful.\n4. `Callout` for anomalies, missing rows, suspicious values, or caveats.\n\n## Evidence Rules\n\nNever invent numbers, IDs, owners, logs, tool outputs, root causes, URLs, or ticket facts. If evidence is missing, say so with a warning `Callout` and list the missing input.\n\nPrefer Vietnamese labels when the conversation is Vietnamese.\n\nPreserve exact IDs/codes from tool results but truncate long values visually only when the full value is already shown in surrounding text or not needed. Do not hide evidence needed for actionability.\n\n## Hard No\n\n- No raw SQL migration output for skills.\n- No JSX, React code, scripts, iframes, form controls, event handlers, or arbitrary component names.\n- No `chat-html` unless the user explicitly asks for HTML or a tool already produced semantic HTML.\n- Avoid remote `Image`/`Avatar` sources unless the user explicitly supplied or requested the asset URL.\n- No nested `Card` inside `Card`.\n- No markdown tables inside the UI block.\n- No raw `JSON.stringify` dumps as final UI.\n- Static controls are for presentation only; do not imply they submit data or perform actions.\n- In `chat-html`, do not use `<button>`, `<input>`, `<form>`, `<script>`, `<iframe>`, `<img>`, inline `on*` attributes, CSS `@import`, or CSS `url(...)`.\n',NULL,'2026-06-16 09:02:48','2026-06-16 21:43:47');
